Because you are <pipe answer age> years old you don’t need to start having Pap tests yet. Once you turn over 18 and have been sexually active for two years you will need to have regular Pap tests. 

A Pap test is a simple test that checks for changes in cells in the cervix caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV) that can lead to cervical cancer. If abnormal cells are present they can be treated to prevent cervical cancer from developing. If you become sexually active, you will still need to have regular Pap tests even if you have had the HPV vaccination. This is because the vaccine does not protect you from all of the strains of HPV that can lead to cervical cancer.

Pap test reminder

You are due for your next Pap test in <date piped from answer to question 6>.

A Pap test is a simple test that checks for changes in cells of the cervix caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV) that can lead to cervical cancer. It is important not to worry about having an abnormal result from a Pap test, as it does not mean that you have cervical cancer. 

Most abnormal results aren’t due to anything serious. When you return an abnormal result from a Pap test you may need to have tests more often than every two years to monitor the changes. If the results from your repeat tests are normal, you may be able to go back to having a Pap test every two years. If the results from repeat tests are still abnormal you may need treatment to prevent cervical cancer from developing.

Because you have never been sexually active you don’t need to start having regular Pap tests yet. 

If you become sexually active you will need a Pap test every two years to check for abnormal cervical cells. Changes in cervical cells can be caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV), which is a common infection that can be passed on through sexual contact. If abnormal cells are detected they can be treated to prevent cervical cancer from developing. 

You will still need to have regular Pap tests even if you have had the HPV vaccination, because the vaccine does not protect you from all of the strains of HPV that can lead to cervical cancer.

cells.contentFull:
Pap test reminder

You should make an appointment to have your first Pap test now. 

Because you have been sexually active for more than two years you need to start having regular Pap tests to check for changes in cells of the cervix. Changes in cervical cells can be caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV), which is a common infection that can be passed on through sexual contact. If abnormal cells are present they can be treated to prevent cervical cancer from developing. 

You still need to have regular Pap tests even if you have had the HPV vaccination, because the vaccine does not protect you from all of the strains of HPV that can lead to cervical cancer.

What to expect
You might feel nervous or embarrassed at the thought of having your first Pap test, but it’s something almost all women go through. Even though having a Pap test may be a little awkward, the procedure only lasts a few minutes and is the best way to protect yourself against cervical cancer.

When you see your doctor to have a Pap test you will be asked to undress from the waist down and given a sheet or a towel to cover yourself with. While you are lying down on an examination table your doctor will gently insert an instrument called a speculum in your vagina. The speculum is a small metal or plastic device that keeps the entrance to your vagina open so that the doctor can see your cervix. They will then use a small spatula and brush to collect a few cells from the cervix. The cells are smeared onto a glass slide and sent to a laboratory for testing.

cells.contentFull:
Pap test

Women who have at least two normal Pap test results in the five years before they turn 70 can stop having Pap tests. This is because the risk of developing cervical cancer over the age of 70 is small. Because you didn’t have regular Pap tests before you turned 70 you may need to keep having tests for a few more years to make sure that the cells in your cervix are normal and not undergoing changes that may lead to cancer.  

You should check with your doctor or the cervical screening register in your state or territory to find out when you can stop having Pap tests. Contact details for the screening registers are available from the National Cervical Screening Program hotline on 13 15 56 or through their webpage: http://www.cancerscreening.gov.au/.
